<note>For <term xml:lang="ta">ētu</term> , explained as Skt. hetu-, "reason", there is at
least one clear parallel in NA 145.5, there too in combination with il: ētillā ūṅku, "[even]
before there was a reason" the mother became attentive.</note>
<note>The sandhi here actually would be resolved as <term xml:lang="ta">maṉṟu</term> , not <term xml:lang="ta">maṉṟa + amma</term> . This is another special case (besides optative in <term xml:lang="ta">-ka + eṉ-tal</term> ) where ending -a is treated like -u.</note>
<note><term xml:lang="ta">ōri</term> , attested twice in the KT and nowhere else in the old
anthologies, is, according to DEDR 1061 only "male jackal", according to the TL "hair of a
male"; in KT 244.4 it seems to denote the crest of a peacock.</note>
